summary.p: 287 fol. (280 fol. original manuscript) on paper; Shelfmark: Is 1431; complete text of the Qurʾān (Q 1-114); 15 lines to the page; Dimensions: 177 x 137 mm; Script style: nasḫī; Dated by colophon to 1000/1 CE (391 AH), copy produced in Baghdad by ʿAlī b. Hilāl, known as Ibn al-Bawwāb (died in 1022 CE).
The catalogue of Qurʾān manuscripts of Chester Beatty Library contains the following information (Arberry 1967, p. 15):

"41. The Koran. Two hundred and eighty-six (two hundred and eighty) folios of firm paper, measuring 17.7 x 13.,7 cm., 15 lines to the page. The script is superb old naskh. The first six and last four pages are fully illuminated. The binding is fairly modern, dark-red flapped. Copyist, ʿAlī ibn Hilāl [Ibn al-Bawwāb]. Dated, at Baghdad, 391 (1000-1). See D.S. Rice, passim; Ettinghausen 1961, pp. 170-1. See Plate 26. (MS. 1431)"

The manuscript contains 280 folios of the original manuscript, of which the first 3 folios and the last 2 folios have illuminations with text other than the Qurʾān.This catalogue entry gives folio numbers as provided by the digital interface of Chester Beatty Library which counts 287 folios, one more than mentioned in Arberry's catalogue entry (see above). The folio numbering of the library counts six paper leafs added for the binding as parts of the manuscript. These added paper leafs are counted in this digital entry by numbers 1-6 because they could not be attributed to precise folio numbers. The Qurʾānic text begins on fol. 9v (Q 1) and runs until fol. 283v (Q 112-114). Page fol. 284r has the colophon written by the scribe ʿAlī b. Hilāl [Ibn al-Bawwāb] (d. 1022); folios 284v, 285r (= plate 26 in Arberry, The Koran illuminated) 285v, and 286r have illuminations.The last leaf, fol. 287 is not original and was added to the manuscript.
